heading: Rambler Maker Increases Profit
summary: Rambler’s sales helped A.M.C. got the first year’s profit since the merger of the Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company in to A.M.C.

heading: Rambler Facing Eroding Market
summary: Rambler’s market share was continually declining under intensive market competition.

heading: American Motors Corp. to Drop Rambler Name
summary: Managers narrowed down Rambler production and blamed sales slide to Rambler’s image.

heading: Market Place Rambler Chief States His Case
summary: It is hard to compete with the Big Three. A.M.C. was the only money losing automobile manufacturer in 1967.

heading: American Motors is Optimistic
summary: A.M.C. is optimistic to the small loss in quarter. The dealer shrinking seemed to be the bigger problem.

heading: Rambler in Black for 3-Month Span
summary: In 1969, A.M.C. reported its first profit in a March quarter since 1965. New model was brought out to improve the sales.

heading: American Motors' Hornet Displaces the Rambler
summary: For changing the model’s image, Rambler was dropped. A.M.C. declared competitive war on the Ford’s model.

heading: A.M.C. Unveils Sub-Compact Car
summary: Rambler helped A.M.C. turned around in mid 1950s and captured 7 percent of the car market for American Motors in 1963.

heading: A.M.C.’s Long, Hard Struggle
summary: A.M.C. struggled in compact car market during late 1960s due to invasions of the Big Three, ‘Beetle’, and Japanese automakers.
